<analysis>
<has-cmf>False. There is no CMF number present in the post.</has-cmf>
<refers-to-candidate>False. The post does not refer to any parliamentary candidate.  It promotes a Romanian jewelry brand, CASIANI.</refers-to-candidate>
<addresses-the-wide-population>True. The post is a paid advertisement on Facebook, a public platform, and uses hashtags to reach a wider audience interested in Romanian businesses, entrepreneurship, and jewelry.</addresses-the-wide-population>
<electoral-objective>False. The objective of the post is to promote the CASIANI jewelry brand. While the advertiser, Oana Bulai, is a member of parliament, the post itself does not advocate for her or any other candidate in the parliamentary elections. The content focuses solely on the brand and its products.</electoral-objective>
<journalism>False. The post is not journalistic in nature. It's a promotional piece for a commercial brand.</journalism>
<personal_opinion>The post expresses a personal opinion about the brand, but this opinion is not related to any political candidate or the parliamentary elections. It's an endorsement of a commercial product.</personal_opinion>
</analysis>

<conclusion>
<post_id>1084210163153924</post_id>
<electoral-propaganda-analysis>
The Facebook post promotes the CASIANI jewelry brand.  While the advertiser, Oana Bulai, is a member of parliament, the post's content is unrelated to the parliamentary elections.  It focuses on the brand's attributes and does not advocate for any political candidate or party.  The hashtags used are related to business promotion and not electoral campaigning. There is no call to action related to voting.  The post does not violate Article 98 t) because it lacks an electoral objective and does not constitute electoral propaganda as defined by Article 36 (7) of LEGE nr. 334 din 17 iulie 2006.
</electoral-propaganda-analysis>
